  "articleSummary": "This article argues that the rigid, dogmatic application of the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP) harms software quality by confusing minimal code size with true conceptual cohesion. Targeting senior developers and architects, it adopts a critical, pragmatic tone to warn against \"Single-Purpose People\" whose purist tendencies lead to fragmented codebases, brittle tests, and stalled velocity, using React/Redux and Unix philosophy as contrasting examples. Recurring metaphors of architectural violence, \"file system shrapnel,\" and Rube Goldberg machines frame the core thesis: modularity should prioritize cohesive, composable units that change together rather than enforced micro-fragmentation.",
